  "doc_id": "16059",
  "text": "It is believed that in these GBS variants, the mechanism of so-called molecular mimicry essentially contributes to the induction of an autoimmune response against peripheral nerve tissue . The observation that microbes express carbohydrate epitopes that resemble glycolipid antigens on the surface of peripheral nerves is the basis for the hypothesis of postinfectious molecular mimicry in GBS. This is best documented for the gram-negative rod Campylobacter jejuni, which can be identified as cause of a preceding infection in up to 60% of all GBS cases. This enteropathogen contains several ganglioside-like moieties on the outer leaflet of its lipooligosaccarides [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
